Explanation of how I derived the Operation object for PUT /v1/users/{user}:

- Controller: app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/UserController.php
  - The update(...) action is responsible for handling PUT /v1/users/{user}.
  - It calls $this->authorize('update', $user) — an authorization gate that can return a 403 Forbidden if the authenticated user is not allowed to update the target user.
  - If the request includes a non-empty password ($request->filled('password')), controller hashes it with Hash::make(...) and merges it into the request before update.
  - The code updates the user with $user->update(array_filter($request->only(['name','email','password']))) — so only name, email, password can be updated, and falsey values are filtered out.
  - The action returns new UserResource($user), so the response body follows the User resource representation.

- Request validation: app/Http/Requests/UsersRequest.php
  - The request rules require 'name' and 'email':
    - name: required, string, max:255, custom AlphaName rule (format constraints enforced by the rule).
    - email: required, must be a valid email, unique:users,email,<current user id> — i.e., email must be unique in users table except the currently authenticated user.
  - Because this is a FormRequest, validation failures will produce a 422 Unprocessable Entity with standard Laravel validation error structure.

- Response resource: app/Http/Resources/User.php and app/Http/Resources/Role.php
  - Returned JSON includes: id, name, email, provider, provider_id, registered_at (ISO8601 datetime), comments_count, posts_count, roles (array of Role objects).
  - Role objects include id and name.

Based on this, the Operation object includes:
- A path parameter "user" (the {user} route parameter). Type integer (typical ID).
- A request body schema for application/json with properties name, email, password. 'name' and 'email' are required per UsersRequest; password is optional and, if provided, will be hashed by the server.
- Responses:
  - 200: application/json response matching the User resource structure.
  - 403: possible when authorization fails.
  - 422: validation error with the standard Laravel validation error format: message and errors object.

